  • [[Nephrology miscellaneous#Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis|Membranoproliferative(aka mesangioproliferative,aka mesangiocapillary) glomerulonephritis]]

[!INFO] Membranoproliferative and Mesangioproliferative are described under "acute nephritic syndromes" in Harrison's
This probably means they present more often as nephritic syndromes but also can have some proteinuria.

  • Type 1: subendothelial immune complex deposition (or interposition of mesangial cells in the subendothelial space) -> splitting of capillary basement membrane -> tramline appearance. (Mnemonic: "All aboard the proliferative train") -> Tramlines
    • Type 1 MPGN is commonly associated with chronic hepatitic C infection
    • Nephrotic range proteinuria is a poor prognostic marker.
    • linear intramembranous-membranous deposits
      Causes of membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis
  1. Autoimmune
  2. Chronic infections

There is (From Harrison's)

  1. Mesangial expansion +/- mesangial hypercellularity.
  2. Single contoured capillary walls
  3. Mesangial immune deposits.
  • Presents with varying degrees of proteinuria and commonly haematuria.
    • Isolated haematuria -> very benign course;
      proteinuria + -> increased risk of renal failure.
  • Most cases are caused by [[#IgA nephropathy]].
  • Falciparum malaria is a cause.

C3 glomerulopathies

  • Two types: Dense deposit disease (DDD) and C3 glomerulpathy. (C3GN)
  • Defined by C3 mediated glomerulonephritis with no immunoglobulin involvement.
  • C3 levels are low with normal C4 levels.
  • The histological patterns of C3 glomerulopathies is most commonly membranoproliferative or mesangioproliferative.
